	<abstract>
		<heading level="2">Abstract</heading>
		<paragraph>
			This research focuses on how to create inclusive and engaging audio-visual experiences for cultural heritage archives.
			By examining the current barriers to accessing and exploring large audi-visual collections and identify how these barriers limit meaningful engagement with cultural content
			Building on these insights, the project aims to develop and evaluate approaches to accessiblity leveraging Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Immersive media technologies to support
			richer forms of discovery, navigation and interpretation. By combining participarty design methods with technical innovation, this research aims to provide both practical guidelines
			and novel concepts that demonstrate how digital archives can be designed with universal access fundamentally embedded within the interface rather than an afterthought.
		</paragraph>
	</abstract>

	<content>
		<section id="introduction">
			<heading level="2">Introduction</heading>
			<paragraph>
				Digitisation has a massive impact on the way heritage material is preserved, accessed and experienced. In the case of audio-visual collections from the Netherlands Institue of Sound&amp;Vision,
				a large portion of the collection that was stored on fragile carriers such as film, magnetic tape, and video tapes has been digitised over the past fifteen years and can now be accessed remotely
				The Sound&amp;Vision collection chronicles historical events and illuminates the intricate relationship between meida, society, and technological progress. Access to this collection is essential
				for citizens with disabilities to engage with their cultural heritage to foster a more inclusive society.
			</paragraph>
		</section>

		<section id="methodology">
			<heading level="2">Methodology</heading>
			<paragraph>
				Participatory reserach and co-creation is a key aspect of our approach, we will work closely with community members with lived experience of disability to understand their needs 
				and preferences. The objective is to holistically emphasize the values of inclusion and agency for disabled communities through continual acts of attunement, embodied adjustments
				and realignments of relationships between researchers and stakeholders, so that the communties drive the decision-making on design approacheds and solutions (servies, technologies,
				policy guidelines). The project will also iteratively co-design, prototype and evaluate inclusive and accessible AI and immersive media-based solutions for discovery, navigation 
				and interpretation of audio-visual cultural heritage content, with a focus on creating engaging and meaningful experiences for users with disabilities.
				
			</paragraph>
			<list type="unordered">
				<item>Define a semantic schema that clearly separates metadata from content.</item>
				<item>Ensure every graphical element includes comprehensive alternative text (alt text).</item>
				<item>Maintain an explicit, logical reading order from top to bottom.</item>
			</list>
		</section>

		<section id="results">
			<heading level="2">Results</heading>
			<paragraph>
				Our tests showed a significant improvement in screen reader compatibility 
				compared to standard un-tagged PDF posters, as the structural semantics 
				are exposed naturally.
			</paragraph>
			<figure id="fig1">
				<image src="chart.png" alt="Bar chart showing a 100% improvement in screen reader parsing speed and user comprehension when using semantically grouped XML over un-tagged PDF."/>
				<caption>Figure 1: Screen Reader Compatibility Comparison</caption>
			</figure>
		</section>

		<section id="conclusion">
			<heading level="2">Conclusion</heading>
			<paragraph>
				Open structural standards like XML provide an effective foundation for 
				creating fully accessible digital academic resources, ensuring research 
				is available to everyone regardless of ability.
			</paragraph>
		</section>
